May 29 2009 	Posh new hotel in an increasing posh city	We stayed 4 nights at the Grand Millennium in December. My husband and I visited Beijing with his parents, and all 4 of us enjoyed our stay very much. We got a good deal as well, as many new hotels needed to boost business after the decline in visitors post-Olympics.The rooms were fairly big and the bed very comfortable. Choice of pillows available. Heating was good. Bathroom was big and well equipped with bath tub and separate shower. Staff was helpful and polite. Not much smiling though, very business like. No trouble communicating with the reception, not as easy with the restaurant staff but I could practice my Mandarin. Buffet breakfast was great except the English tea tastes a bit different. If you drink Chinese tea then it's fine. The location was perfect because it was in the heart of the financial centre, right next door to where our expat friend was living. Less than 30 min from the airport (except rush hour as the traffic in Beijing can be quite a nightmare) by taxi, which costs about 100 RMB. Since the financial district is the new trendy area, restaurants around here tend to be more expensive (100+ RMB pp) but also better quality. Try the restaurant inside the Ritan Park and the hotpot place across the road. We also tried some local dumpling places in the old city Hutongs (alleys), where the 4 of us were fed for a mere total of 15 RMB. This gives you an idea of the rich-poor gap in this city.Beijing in December was freezing (-10 oC by day) and we went everywhere in the city by taxi, which was so cheap. Tiananmen Square, Forbidden City etc all within a 30 RMB (15 min) ride. For the Olympic village we took the brand new subway line. So cheap. For the Great wall and summer palace (further out from the city), our friend arranged chauffeur service at 600 RMB for a whole day. The hotel would arrange that too, perhaps a bit more expensive. The bit of Great wall that we went to (Badaling) was very popular amongst tourist, hence with better facilities (gondolas for those who do not wish to walk, even a roller coaster for the downward trip). Our driver suggested that next time we can try the 'wild Great wall' sections - no hand rails, no staircase, no toilet, no souvenir shops, but he did not recommend that for our parents.All in all, Beijing is a city with something for everyone. From the spectacular forbidden city to the charming alleys still filled with the smell of coal, to the trendy art shops in the 798 art district. (798 used to be a weapon factory), we enjoyed our stay very much. You still see the 'flying swords' (spitting) once in while, usually by older men, but the general population are very friendly to tourists, thanks to the Olympics effect. And the Grand Millennium is a posh new hotel to explore the improving city.	
Mar 25 2009 	Excellent Hotel Will Return On My Next Visit	Room:What can I say! This room was new, large and luxurious! Spacious work desk (with free internet). Comfortable bed with reading light and Large LCD TV. Day bed was also provided beside the Window and gave a good view of the City. Toilet area was hugh and connected to the room (you could pull a sliding door for privacy). Separate 'Spa' Shower and WC area, also Bath Tub was located near window too.Breakfast:The breakfast room located at the ground was classy. The menu was delightful with plenty of choices. From American Breakfast of Fried Eggs, Sussages and Bacon to China Porridge to Rice Dishes to Japanese Roll to Dessert Tarts. Freshly brewed coffee was served every morning. Facilities:Excellent and large gym with excellent weights and aerobic equipment. But best of all was the 25m lap pool!Service staff:From counter staff, kitchen staff, waiting staff, front desk, bell-boys and Concerige. Excellent, Courteous and Attentive. Location:Nothing interesting nearby but there was a shopping mall within a short 5 mins walk World Trade Center was 10 mins walk and the famour Silk Plaza was around 15 mins walk. The Local Underground Transit Stop was located just outside the hotel but I did not use. Note that this hotel is just open and very new and I can detect a slight 'smell' in the hallways and pool, not so evident in the room (probably still need some airing). Nothing too offensive but definitely there. Also not all taxt will know this hotel, so do a print a copy of the Map.	
